<TEXT>
nearly 60 house members are asking the bush 
administration to move towards establishing diplomatic relations 
with sovietbacked angola 
rep howard wolpe dmich chairman of the house foreign 
affairs subcommittee on africa introduced the resolution 
wednesday saying it is in the interest of the united states to 
take immediate and significant measures to normalize relations with 
the government of angola 
the resolution signed by 42 democrats and 15 republicans calls 
for the united states to establish a liaison office in luanda the 
capital for support of angolas full participation in the world 
bank and international monetary fund and for us assistance to 
help angola rebuild its warravaged economy 
meanwhile lawmakers from both chambers have invited jose 
eduardo dos santos the president of angola to visit the united 
states as soon as possible to explore with you the perspective of 
the angolan government on a range of issues 
among the 34 people signing that letter which was dated sept 
21 were sens paul simon dill chairman of the senate foreign 
relations africa subcommittee and edward m kennedy dmass 
the congressional actions come as members of congress are 
debating the future of us policy on angola an oilrich country 
in southeastern africa where civil war has raged for nearly 14 
years 
some democrats led by wolpe have charged the bush 
administration is too biased in favor of jonas savimbi the rebel 
leader who has fought the central marxist government for over a 
decade 
the united states provides as much as 50 million to savimbi in 
what experts believe is one of the largest military covert aid 
programs in the world savimbi is scheduled to come to the united 
states to lobby for more money next week 
republicans and administration officials contend however that 
dos santos sovietbacked government is to blame for the failure 
of peace efforts to end the conflict 
there is absolutely no question that the major obstacle to 
peace is the intransigence and duplicity of the communist 
dictatorship in luanda said rep dan burton rill 
he said it is unlikely the government would ever agree to 
voluntarily share governing power with savimbis forces 
if we do not keep up the pressure on them at this critical 
juncture there will be no hope for reconciliation he said 
wolpe said at a hearing wednesday that administration officials 
are hampering peace prospects by failing to deal fairly with the 
angolan government 
us policy towards angola is simply not working he said 
now is an appropriate moment to advance the public debate of us 
policy to question whether policy should be determined by rigid 
ideological commitments or whether there is a possibility for 
greater rationality and balance in us foreign policy 
another democrat rep george crockett of michigan charged that 
the state department policy plays into the hands of south 
africa south africa provides aid to savimbi 
but warren clark the assistant secretary of state for african 
affairs said washington will continue to support savimbi until a 
reconciliation between the two sides in angola is achieved 
the administration believes that lasting peace and national 
reconciliation can take place only in a scenario in which there are 
no losers only winners he said 
clark dismissed the idea of diplomatic links with angola until 
national reconciliation is achieved 
