<TEXT>
those southern boll weevils who gave the 
house democratic leadership fits early in the reagan 
administration are on the rise again 
this time conservative southern legislators are swing votes in 
the confrontation between president bush and house leaders over 
conflicting tax plans 
to win approval of his plan to cut the tax rate for capital 
gains bush will need strong support from southern democrats he 
got it on the house ways and means committee when six democrats 
five of them southerners joined republicans to support bush over 
their committee chairman rep dan rostenkowski dill 
the democratic leadership offered an alternative plan that would 
revive the deduction for individual retirement accounts and pay for 
it by raising taxes on the richest 600000 couples and individuals 
few of the 1981 boll weevils remain in the house but their 
ideological heirs are prime targets of lobbying on the competing 
tax bills 
the bush proposal gives a tax break for the rich paid for by 
the middle class our proposal gives individual retirement accounts 
to the middle class paid for by the superwealthy is the way 
house majority leader richard gephardt defines the issue 
the white house portrays the leadership alternative as another 
democratic proposal to raise taxes 
many southerners are siding with the president particularly 
those whose districts include hundreds of small farmers and 
businessmen timber owners and real estate investors they reject 
the idea that a capital gains tax cut benefits only the wealthy 
timber is the number one industry in georgia and i have no 
qualms in speaking out for it said democratic rep lindsay 
thomas 
weve made our case and there are many people in congress 
who have listened and thats what the party leadership is not 
listening to he said weve got to start talking about 
assisting the middleincome people whove been defecting from our 
party 
but the new boll weevils are far from united on the issue 
rep charles stenholm dtexas a leader of the 1981 defection 
to reagan is backing the leadership bill saying that a capital 
gains cut now would increase the federal deficit 
in georgia and alabama only one of 14 house democrats indicated 
support for the leadership alternative three others were 
undecided but the rest said they were solidly behind the capital 
gains reduction 
rep ben erdreich dala said he has been a longtime 
supporter of a lower tax rate for capital gains and does not intend 
to abandon that position for a plan that includes a tax increase of 
nearly 40 billion 
theres no question that what they the leadership have 
fashioned is appealing but i just have a problem starting out with 
a tax increase at the front end of budget deliberations erdreich 
said 
the democratic leaderships plan would raise the tax rate for 
family income above 155000 and individual income above 93000 
from 28 percent to 33 percent the 33 percent rate now applies only 
to family income between 74850 and 155000 and individual income 
between 44900 and 93000 
the plan also would provide a scaleddown capital gains tax 
break by eliminating the 33 percent bracket for capital gains so 
that the tax on profits from asset sales would never climb above 28 
percent 
rep buddy darden dga said he voted against the 1986 tax 
reform law because it eliminated ira deductions but he said he 
wont support the leadership alternative because i frankly doubt 
the sincerity of this plan since it was created for the sole 
purpose of derailing the capital gains reduction 
rep roy rowland dga is particularly sensitive to charges of 
party disloyalty since he won his seat in 1982 by criticizing his 
boll weevil democratic opponent for supporting the reagan economic 
program 
i dont like to call myself a boll weevil he said i look 
at myself as a moderatetoconservative democrat who has some 
allegiance to the leadership in the house 
but my primary responsibility is to the people in my district 
and my district is the largest timberproducing district that is 
privately owned in the us he said there are a lot of people 
who are small landowners and small timber owners who are going to 
be helped by this capital gains reduction 
