<TEXT>
the chairman of the senate agriculture 
committee expressing reservations about president bushs choice 
for a top agriculture department post says he doesnt want a 
james watt clone in the job 
sen patrick leahy dvt opened confirmation hearings 
wednesday for james cason whose tenure as an interior department 
official was strongly criticized by environmentalists by saying he 
had serious reservations about cason 
cason was nominated by bush to be assistant secretary of 
agriculture for natural resources and the environment the 
departments job overseeing national forest land and agricultural 
conservation programs 
mr cason has no professional training in forest landuse 
stewardship and neither training nor experience in soil and water 
conservation said leahy 
leahy and other committee members pressed cason for four hours 
about decisions he made during his seven years at the interior 
department 
environmentalists have charged that cason in 1986 tried to 
prevent a report from becoming public that said the spotted owls 
existence could be endangered by the harvesting of old growth 
forest in the pacific northwest 
cason told leahy he did not try to hide the report saying 
changes needed to be made and he was holding it until it was 
cleaned up 
cason 35 also said that contrary to accusations he did 
nothing to hold up a petition to prevent listing the spotted owl as 
an endangered species 
he also defended the sale of land under his jurisdiction at well 
below market costs to private interests who made large profits by 
reselling the properties sen kent conrad said that in one 
instance an 1872 law was used to sell land for 42000 to private 
interests who sold it a few weeks later for 37 million 
the sale was one of several actions cason took in the final 
three weeks of the reagan administration some of which were either 
stopped or reversed by president bushs interior secretary manuel 
lujan 
cason said he had been working on the sale for two years and 
wanted to get it finished before the next administration came in 
and that he had been following a mandate from thensecretary donald 
hodel to continue with business despite the impending change in 
administrations 
decisions by cason that were changed by lujan included an audit 
agreement with 12 major oil companies that would have caused states 
and indian tribes to lose royalty payments and a policy that would 
have allowed surface mining in national parks 
what appears here is not just doing the job said leahy 
but an overabundance of zeal 
in his opening statement leahy said we are at a time when a 
strong and heightened awareness of the environment is needed in the 
department of agriculture a spirit of cooperation among all 
interests has to prevail 
we do not need a james watt clone in this position 
the agriculture committee has scheduled an oct 3 hearing for 
environmental groups to give their views on cason 
