<TEXT>
two researchers say the financial setup of the 
olympic games is a travesty that demands enormous sums from the 
american networks while giving sports coverage to other nations at 
cut rates 
those other countries can turn their savings into big subsidies 
for their athletes the authors contend in their study fools 
gold how america pays to lose in the olympics 
nbc paid 300 million for the rights to the 1988 summer olympics 
in seoul and needed 5000 commercials in 179 hours of air time to 
recover its costs robert z lawrence and jeffrey d pellegrom note 
in the study for the brookings institution 
even then the network later returned 70 million to advertisers 
because of low ratings they say in the fall issue of the brookings 
review 
abc paid 309 million bid for the us rights to the 1988 winter 
olympics in calgary and lost some 65 million when expenses 
exceeded advertising revenue 
eastern europe and the soviet union meanwhile paid only 3 
million combined to get rights to the seoul games western europe 
negotiating through a single body paid just 57 million total for 
the calgary rights 
the study says that after each competing nation receives a share 
of the tv monies from olympics organizers the soviet union and 
east germany may be getting more back than they spend on tv rights 
the east bloc nations may then lavish funds on their athletes 
the funding setup for the olympics is a travesty the 
authors say 
we pay more than our fair share for the games we have to put 
up with an excessive number of commercials to see them and our 
athletes receive little of the money we do pay they say 
the ioc divides the money between the host city judges and 
officials media centers the national olympic committees and the 
ioc itself 
the us olympic committee got 25 percent of the 609 million 
abc and nbc paid for the summer and winter games in 1988 the study 
says usocs share for the 1992 games for which cbs and nbc are 
paying 644 million will be 10 percent 
lawrence and pellegrom suggest the us government and the us 
olympic committee form a joint entity that would auction the us 
television rights that group then would negotiate for us tv 
rights with the ioc as other nations do 
presuming the auction amount is higher than what is finally paid 
to the ioc the excess money could be used to support athletes the 
authors say 
congress might have to grant the networks an antitrust exemption 
for them to bid together 
cbs on wednesday refused comment on the article and nbc 
officials did not return a call seeking reaction 
dennis swanson president of abc sports said we have no 
response on any proposals at this time 
one network official speaking on condition of anonymity said 
he did not see how a governmentusoc body could make substantial 
changes also the official said we dont think it is the burden 
of the networks to finance the training of the athletes 
he denied the networks were overbidding 
when a network bids on a rights package they take a look 
at what its value is obviously networks arent going to be 
spending money that they cant justify 
lawrence and pellegrom acknowledge most foreign tv networks are 
noncommercial and public owned and cant afford huge fees but say 
there are an increasing number of commercial networks and the 
american networks no longer should have to foot the olympics bill 
lawrence is a senior fellow in economic studies at the brookings 
institution a washington think tank pellegrom is a research 
assistant 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

