<DOCNO> AP890928-0029 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
additional safety tests ordered on the three 
savannah river reactors that produce a gas needed for nuclear 
warheads could lead to further delays in restarting the idled 
reactors 
the order announced wednesday by energy secretary james d 
watkins marked a switch from his earlier position that the tests 
need not be completed before restarting the reactors which have 
been plagued by various mechanical problems 
in a related development watkins confirmed the department was 
considering a possible twoyear delay in underground testing at 
yucca mountain a nevada desert site being studied for use as the 
first permanent dump for nuclear waste 
the savannah river complex near aiken sc is the nations 
only source of tritium a radioactive gas used to boost the 
explosive power of nuclear warheads all three reactors have been 
shut down for more than a year for repairs 
watkins made no mention of a possible restart delay his 
spokeswoman christina sankey said later it was too early to 
tell whether a delay was likely 
watkins announced sept 7 that the first of the three savannah 
river reactors would begin lowpower testing late next summer and 
would start production by the end of 1990 he ordered ultrasonic 
testing of the reactor vessels to begin immediately but he did not 
require completion of the tests before restart 
ms sankey said watkins changed his mind about the testing after 
some of his own advisers said it should be completed in all three 
reactors before any one is restarted 
the timing of a savannah river restart is viewed by the bush 
administration as critical because of dwindling supplies of the 
gas tritium decays relatively rapidly and therefore must be 
replenished to keep nuclear weapons fully operational 
the savannah river reactors have had a history of cracks and 
leaks in the primary cooling system pipes as well as flaws in the 
backup cooling systems a leak from a crack in the vessel of 
another savannah river reactor known as c reactor was discovered 
in 1984 that led to its permanent shutdown a year later 
watkins also announced that ultrasonic testing that began 
recently on the p reactor vessel at savannah river had discovered 
a potential indication of a crack in excess of nine inches 
in the area of a welded seam he said the finding is still being 
studied and that further tests are being performed on the p reactor 
he said the significance of the problem had not yet been 
determined although ms sankey said later were quite confident 
there is no crack in the vessel 
ms sankey said there was no technical reason to condition a 
k reactor restart on completion of the ultrasonic testing but that 
watkins chose to impose the condition in order to instill greater 
public confidence in the restart program 
in ultrasonic testing sound waves are bounced off the reactor 
vessel and any abnormalities show up as breaks in the waves 
restarting the savannah river reactors and completing a 
