<TEXT>
yugoslavias parliament today asked 
the supreme court to urgently rule on whether the northern republic 
of slovenia has the right to secede from the federation 
amendments to slovenias constitution adopted wednesday give its 
legislature the right to secede and provide for strict controls by 
slovenia over the use of the yugoslav armed forces in the region in 
peacetime 
they also pave the way for introduction of a westernstyle 
multiparty democracy in the republic bordering on italy and 
austria several independent opposition parties have already been 
formed in the republic 
antislovenian protest rallies and staterun media in some 
southern parts of yugoslavia demanded tough action against the most 
liberal of its six member republics 
slovenian authorities have repeatedly stressed they do not plan 
to secede and that the changes only provide an added sense of 
security for the 2 million slovenes who make up about 8 percent 
of yugoslavias population 
but slovenias actions have met with strong opposition in 
serbia whose leadership advocates limiting regional autonomy and 
introducing greater central controls 
enactment of the changes came in the wake of warnings by the 
federal leadership that they conflicted with the national 
constitution there was even speculation that martial law might be 
imposed in the region 
authorities dissuaded several thousand belgrade students from 
staging a demonstration today in front of the downtown federal 
parliament building university sources told the associated press 
the students were demanding that the federal authorities take 
all necessary measures to ensure the integrity of yugoslavia the 
sources said 
belgrade radio reported a spate of smaller protest gatherings in 
several towns in the countrys largest republic of serbia up to 
50000 people demonstrated in montenegro on wednesday demanding 
the toppling of the slovenian leadership 
zarija martinovic a serbian deputy in the federal parliament 
demanded that yugoslavias constitutional court immediately review 
the constitutionality of the slovenian action 
but marjan rozic a slovenian asked that the court also 
consider all other constitutional amendments including serbias 
which caused demonstrations by ethnic albanians in the southern 
province of kosovo in march that left at least 24 people dead the 
changes gave serbia more control over the province 
both proposals were accepted by the parliament the state tanjug 
news agency said 
yugoslavia consists of six republics and two autonomous 
provinces each with its own government and party structure the 
decentralized system of government and collective federal 
presidency were devised in 1974 to prevent one republic from 
gaining sway over the others but it has resulted in an ineffective 
government by compromise 
