<TEXT>
soviet socialism should get out of the housing 
business and turn it over to a system condemned for decades as the 
root of evil private ownership a lawyer was quoted as saying 
thursday 
the lawyer a movye of moscow said in the communist party 
daily pravda that giving away millions of stateowned apartments to 
their occupants would save the cost of maintaining them make 
people more mobile and save the hassle of selling individual 
apartments only to those who can afford full price 
besides he argued people have already paid for the basically 
shabby array of stateowned apartments through a variety of 
indirect taxes people also pay a nominal rent 
pravda ran movyes lengthy article on its second page under the 
headline more profitable to give than to sell and with the 
subheading for the agenda of the supreme soviet it appeared 
the newspaper was endorsing the idea but it might merely have been 
endorsing discussion of the issue 
movyes proposal came at a time when some members of the supreme 
soviet legislature are urging that a measure of private property be 
reintroduced into a system that has crushed most forms of private 
ownership 
a law on property is going before the legislature during the 
fall session that opened monday and a group of reformminded 
deputies on sunday endorsed a call for legalization of private 
property 
the groups leader boris yeltsin told supporters last week he 
believes 10 percent of the property in the soviet union should be 
turned over to private owners 
movye said economic reforms that include cutting unneeded 
workers in a drive for greater efficiency are going to redistribute 
the soviet work force and the only way to ensure housing in new 
areas is to take it out from under central control 
currently about one in five soviet families must share 
apartments the vast majority of apartments are owned by the state 
are cramped and rented for very low prices 
a minority own their own apartments in cooperative buildings 
and in rural areas people are allowed to own or build their own 
houses or summer cottages 
a kremlin directive calls for every soviet family to have its 
own apartment by the year 2000 
but where should they be built in what cities movye asked 
no planning or other kind of agency is in a position to make such 
an accounting in a huge country 
people will be more willing to move for work purposes if they 
think they can obtain an apartment on their own rather than wait in 
line for a stateowned apartment he said 
movye in criticizing current law limiting the rights of 
cooperative owners to sell their apartments appeared to support 
the idea that people should be allowed to buy and sell the homes 
the government would give them 
the government now spends large sums of money as a landlord on 
upkeep and staff for its buildings and could trim those sums from 
its deficit budgets if apartments simply were given away to their 
occupants 
i think it is necessary not to sell but to freely 
transfer to personal property all apartments in buildings of the 
state and social funds he said 
in other words reestablish social justice and transfer to 
workers that which by right belongs to them he said although 
people pay the nominal rent they have basically paid the 
government for construction costs with a variety of hidden taxes 
he said 
the piecemeal sale of some apartments is no solution because 
private and state ownership in government buildings is 
incompatible movye said 
he said the legislature should form a committee to deal with 
soviets who because of special privilege live in especially large 
apartments 
movye also attacked the system of residence permits by which it 
is illegal for soviets to live anywhere without first receiving 
permission from local authorities 
while workers in virtually any country are free to move to find 
new work if they lose their jobs soviets are tied down by their 
residence permits he said 
some radical lawmakers also have called for elimination of the 
residence permits 
</TEXT>
