<TEXT>
the government announced thursday it 
is seeking a 25 percent cut in lowlevel flying exercises that have 
been the target of national protests since a crash at an air show 
last year killed 70 people 
defense minister gerhard stoltenberg introduced the proposed 
reductions aimed at cutting noise and protecting populated areas 
from accident hazards during a session of the parliaments defense 
committee 
stoltenberg told reporters later that the changes were worked 
out in conjunction with the united states and other nato countries 
that have aircraft and pilots stationed in west germany 
one tactical training center involved in lowlevel flying 
exercises is being relocated to neighboring belgium and 
negotiations are continuing with other allies to export more of the 
missions stoltenberg said 
of the 68000 hours of lowlevel training exercises flown over 
west german territory this year only about 23000 involve west 
german air force aircraft and personnel 
west germans have staged noisy demonstrations over the past year 
against lowflying and other military exercises 
the protesters have accused the government of failing to assert 
its sovereignty in getting nato to reduce the number of disruptive 
maneuvers turning the issue into a major political battle between 
the governing conservativeled coalition and opposition leftists 
opposition has intensified since aug 28 1988 when three 
italian planes crashed during an air show at the us air base at 
ramstein seventy people died when the flaming wreckage flew into 
the crowd of spectators 
another crash on dec 8 in the city of remscheid killed six 
west germans and the american pilot 
neither of the disasters involved lowflying exercises but they 
stirred up broad opposition to the foreign military presence in 
west germany 
the leftist social democrats have been campaigning for a ban on 
lowlevel training flights 
a full halt to lowlevel flying would put our commitment to 
the nato alliance in question stoltenberg told reporters 
instead he said the ministry has worked out a number of 
measures to address public concerns including 
a 25 percent reduction in lowlevel training flights over west 
german territory 
a 50 percent reduction of west german air force training 
flights already put into force 
an increase in the number of areas offlimits to exercises 
from 25 to 61 densely populated municipal regions 
a midday break in the exercises in summer months and no 
flights on weekends and holidays 
reduction of maximum allowable speeds from 1336 mph to 1244 
mph to cut noise from the exercises 
as the measures already reportedly have allied backing they are 
expected to be approved by the parliament 
</TEXT>
