<TEXT>
the pen international writers association met 
thursday with an empty chair for vaclav havel the czech playwright 
whose government barred him from attending 
instead havel sent a message asking for support for all writers 
who face persecution 
havel had been invited to appear on a panel at the session 
titled the writer and the exercise of freedom havels passport 
was confiscated 20 years ago however and his recent application 
for a new one was denied 
jeanguy pilon the quebec writer who led thursdays panel 
referred to the empty chair and said this is a silent testimony 
yet an eloquent testimony to the exercise of freedom by a writer 
he noted that havels work has appeared on the worlds stages 
everywhere but in his native country 
in his message read to the conference havel said if a 
single writer in our country is in chains then there are some 
links of that chain that bind us all 
he referred not to his own legal troubles but to those of three 
other czech writers ivan jirous frantisek starek and petr 
cibulka whom havel said were imprisoned for their writings or for 
publishing others work 
every voice raised in their defense is immensely important 
both to them personally and to us all havel wrote and so 
your public support for these three friends of mine will not just 
be an act of general humanity it will be in the interest of us 
all in the interest of a free and truly authentic literature 
unbound by the agenda of any power 
havel was released from prison may 17 midway through an 
eightmonth jail sentence on charges of incitement and obstructing 
a police officer 
he was charged in january after attending a memorial for jan 
palach a student who set himself on fire and burned to death in 
january 1969 to protest the sovietled invasion a year earlier that 
crushed the a reform movement 
the increasing links between eastern and western writers as a 
result of social and political reforms in the soviet bloc have been 
emphasized at the pen congress 
czechoslovakias leadership however has resisted the reforms 
two delegates from a new soviet chapter based in moscow attended 
the world congress this year for the first time the chapter was 
admitted last may ending a 65year quarrel between moscow and pen 
the international association of poets playwrights editors 
essayists and novelists 
the czech chapter was declared dormant after the 1968 invasion 
but is seeking to be reactivated 
canada is the host of the pen world congress for the first time 
since the association was formed in 1921 the englishspeaking 
canadian chapter organized a twoday session in toronto before the 
conference moved wednesday to montreal for a session sponsored by 
the frenchspeaking chapter 
betty friedan the american author and feminist also was on the 
thursday panel and said threats to freedom of expression can be 
more subtle but still exist in countries such as the united states 
and canada 
i can tell you this from my personal experience as a writer 
and a woman said the author of the feminine mystique a 
classic on womens liberation 
she said writing about women as anything other than the 
acceptable postworld war ii images such as housewife and sex 
object was virtually impossible when her book was published more 
than 25 years ago 
