<DOCNO> AP890928-0134 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration on 
thursday prohibited any aircraft from flying the remains of 
ferdinand e marcos out of the united states for the philippines 
the emergency regulation was issued after a request from the 
state department which said a plane carrying the former philippine 
presidents remains would create a danger to the safety of the 
aircraft and persons involved 
marcos died early thursday in a honolulu hospital where he had 
been treated for 10 months for a series of ailments marcos who 
died at 72 had come to the united states in february 1986 after an 
election and popular revolt ended his 20year rule and installed 
corazon aquino as president 
mrs aquino in reacting to marcos death reiterated a 
government decision to bar the return of his body in the interest 
of safety of those who will take the death of mr marcos in widely 
and passionately conflicting ways and for the tranquility of the 
state and the order of society 
prior to his death marcos wife imelda vowed to take the 
remains back to his homeland 
faa spokesman john leyden said the agency has a range of fines 
and other actions that can be taken against a pilot or air operator 
who violates regulations the maximum fine is 10000 for airplane 
owners and 1000 for individuals for each instance but a pilot or 
plane operator could also lose their flight certificates depending 
on the circumstances leyden said 
the emergency regulation prohibits flight with marcos remains 
from anywhere in the united states to any point in the philippines 
or to any intermediate destination on a flight whose ultimate 
destination is the philippines 
the regulation remains in effect until oct 1 1990 and could 
be extended the faa said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

