<TEXT>
president bush and the nations 
governors agreed today on goals for traditionshattering reform 
of troubled american schools including an antidrug campaign 
reducing dropouts and slashing government red tape 
weve reached agreement on the need for national performance 
goals on the need for more flexibility and accountability the 
need for restructuring and choice and the need for more federal 
support for the prekindergarten education process bush said in 
a sunsplashed ceremony ending a twoday education summit at the 
university of virginia 
speaking on the lawn outside the university rotunda the 
president pledged my determination to follow up in every way 
possible on the accord he reached with the governors 
we just cannot let it sit here and end here and i promise you 
that i wont my cabinet wont and my entire administration will 
not he said 
gov booth gardner dwash reflecting a widespread concern 
among the governors said any additional federal aid that becomes 
available will be applied to the issue of early childhood education 
and head start 
the agreement was announced by bush gardner and gov terry 
branstad of iowa chairman of the national governors association 
after the president had outlined his views on the school crisis 
from this day forward let us be an america of tougher 
standards an america of higher goals and a land of bigger 
dreams bush said at a midday convocation with governors 
educators and students at the university of virginia 
the president pledged to loosen federal restrictions on the 
states and urged the governors in turn to relax their regulatory 
hold on local schools 
calling for national goals by which to judge the performance of 
schools and students bush said there must be a new spirit of 
competition between students between teachers and between schools 
a report card for all 
and to get results he said we will need discipline 
structure and goals 
bush added the american people are ready for radical reforms 
we must not disappoint them 
the president called for traditionshattering reform in 
several areas 
he said every student should be literate enough to know not only 
their three rs but why americans died at bunker hill at 
gettysburg and at monte cassino 
bush also urged allowing parents to choose which schools their 
children attend and said there must be new more accurate ways of 
evaluating schools and making educators more accountable for 
classroom performance 
the president said the education system must never settle for 
the minimum in academics or in behavior decades of research bear 
out what the best teachers already know when standards and 
expectations are high everyone does better 
on the sensitive issue of financing reforms bush said 
to those who say that money alone is the answer i say that 
there is no one answer if anything hard experience teaches that 
we are simply not getting our moneys worth in education our focus 
must no longer be on resources it must be on results 
the statement of summit goals drafted at an early morning 
meeting of white house aides and a delegation of leading governors 
included these proposals 
helping all children prepare for school through nutrition 
programs head start care for needy preschoolers and other programs 
aimed at overcoming the effects of poverty 
restructuring the school system to make educators more 
accountable for their pupils classroom performance 
keeping drugs out of schools 
bolstering onthejob education to make sure american workers 
can meet competition from abroad 
improving literacy in a nation where an estimated 23 million 
adults are classified as functionally illiterate 
providing more flexibility for educators by reducing federal 
and state government regulations 
renewed efforts to reduce a national dropout rate approaching 
30 percent 
neither white house aides nor the governors offered an estimate 
of how much the longterm school reforms would cost or how they 
would be financed 
although bush has rejected any major new federal spending 
initiatives white house chief of staff john sununu said the 
president was impressed by the governors widespread support for 
early childhood programs such as head start he suggested that bush 
would continue to give them a high budget priority 
despite bushs apparent satisfaction with the summits work 
former education secretary william bennett told reporters the 
closed sessions were marred by uninformed discussions and partisan 
pap 
