<TEXT>
head start the federal preschool 
program was singled out for praise by governor after governor at 
the education summit but there was no indication they had 
persuaded president bush to provide enough money for all poor 
toddlers to attend 
still supporters of the program could claim at least a bit of 
progress thursdays concluding joint statement by bush and the 
governors said in regard to federal education money we urge that 
priority for any further funding increases be given to prepare 
young children to succeed in school 
bush himself in his speech to the governors made a point of 
noting that his education proposals to congress last spring 
included an increase in funding for head start 
however bushs proposed increase about 250 million for a 
12 billion program falls far short of what many governors and 
educators say is needed 
it is a good program it works but it is not available except 
to about 27 percent of the eligible students complained 
colorado gov roy romer a democrat 
other governors said bushs press secretary marlin fitzwater 
also indicated to the president during summit working sessions that 
early child programs including head start can be critical in 
terms of ultimate educational success for children who would 
otherwise start school at a disadvantage to kids from welloff 
families 
and a list of goals drafted by white house aides and a 
delegation of leading governors at the summit included helping all 
children prepare for school through nutrition programs head start 
care for needy preschoolers and other programs aimed at overcoming 
the effects of poverty 
but again no talk of full funding 
arkansas gov bill clinton a democrat recalled that during the 
presidential campaign bush said he favored the idea that all 
disadvantaged 4yearolds be covered 
however clinton indicated that governors spending much time 
fighting for funding for head start at the summit would have been 
a very foolish expenditure of our time when we have so much 
more to fight over argue about or work through 
theres a difference of opinions among democrats and a 
difference of opinions among republicans said clinton gov 
carroll campbell a south carolina republican and i would like 
to see our children covered with head start funds but its a 
mistake to think thats the sole subject of the summit 
head start begun as part of president lyndon johnsons war on 
poverty in 1965 serves about 452000 youngsters including 13 
percent handicapped estimates are that there are 24 million 
eligible children 
about 12 billion was spent on the program this year the 
national education association estimates about 63 billion is 
needed to serve all eligible children aged 3 through 5 
certainly head start has been a fine program said education 
secretary lauro cavazos in an interview the problem that were 
getting into is the funding issue again 
all youve got to do is look at the federal budget and its 
clear that theres no room for a lot of new programs and a lot of 
expansion activity he said thats not to say that as a 
department were not going to push early childhood education we 
certainly believe thats a part of it 
head start is administered by the administration on children 
youth and families within the department of health and human 
services not the education department it started as an eightweek 
summer program to help disadvantaged youngsters catch up with 
wealthier children so that they could enter first grade on an equal 
footing 
rules say 80 percent of enrolled children must be from families 
at or below the poverty level 
frequently touted by liberals and conservatives alike the 
program has a proven track record of improving childrens 
performance on school achievement tests helping them learn social 
skills and improving parents attitudes toward their children 
the program also provides medical and nutritional services 
the council on competitiveness said a review of head start 
evaluation studies shows that the program also helps to reduce 
school absenteeism and health problems and lowers the likelihood 
that a student will drop out of the education system 
bushs proposed increase of 250 million would allow an 
additional 90000 children to receive services officials say 
both houses of congress have approved authorization for the 
extra money but in different pieces of legislation 
</TEXT>
