<TEXT>
rare wine from a danish castle cellar that was 
hidden from the invading germans in world war ii sold for 162000 
on thursday the auctioneers christies said 
all of the nearly 3000 bottles of wine most of them french 
were sold by the owner of the 1100yearold aalholm castle near 
nysted in southern denmark the chief buyers were two collectors a 
belgian and a norwegian the londonbased auction house said 
michael broadbent head of christies wine department said the 
germans who invaded denmark in 1940 visited the castle but never 
found the wine cellar 
the family were afraid that the germans would drink all their 
wine so the entrance door was bricked up and there appeared to be 
nothing behind the wall he said 
a secret entrance was made by digging a hole through the 
kitchen floor next to the stove and constructing a shaft covered 
with a trapdoor concealed under a basket of logs 
many of the wines had been undisturbed for decades after being 
shipped to the castle in casks and bottled in the cellar by the 
butler 
the owner baron johanotto rabenlevetzau does not entertain 
on the scale of his forebears and as the stock of older wines is 
too large to be consumed by his family and he needs more space he 
decided to thin out the older vintages dating from the late 19th 
century broadbent said 
