legislation he calls federal inspection for seafood healthfulness 
or the fish act of 1989 it puts the agriculture department in 
charge of inspecting seafood much the way it does meat and poultry 
rep dan glickman dkan came out with the consumer seafood 
safety act which splits the responsibility between usda and the 
food and drug administration 
the fda and national academy of standards have the most 
experience in establishing scientific standards to protect against 
adulteration by which food should be inspected glickman said 
the usda has inspection expertise that can be relied upon to 
effectively carry out the guidelines established at fda 
de la garza said the inspection should be in usda where 
historically the food inspection process has been from the 
beginning 
another seafood inspection measure is being worked on by the 
house energy and commerce committee and similar proposals also 
have been introduced in the senate 
all are attempts to reassure consumers who cut back their 
consumption of seafood last year after 10 years of steady increases 
seafood is the only flesh food in the united states not subject 
to comprehensive and rigorous mandatory safety inspection by the 
federal government 
both consumer and industry groups favor strengthening the 
regulations 
