<TEXT>
residents who suffered damage to their 
homes and property from hurricane hugos fury can expect to feel 
shock anger depression anxiety and a whole range of emotional 
pain experts say 
theres so many emotions going on right now almost 
everybodys had some major disruptions theyre going to have to 
deal with their losses sharon foley a social worker at southern 
pines psychiatric hospital in charleston said wednesday 
the emotional upheaval may result in nightmares sleep disorders 
and jumpiness some feelings may last for weeks months or even a 
year doctors said 
hugo was an experience of being immersed in chaos of people 
losing everything they possessed of not knowing if they would be 
alive said dr linda austin associate professor of psychiatry 
at medical university of south carolina 
it really rattled us to our roots said austin coordinator 
of the schools crisis response effort to the killer storm which 
was blamed for 29 deaths in the united states 
one of the most common emotions is that of anger 
what were angry at is that hurricane hugo came and demolished 
our homes and our beautiful city but how do you get mad at a 
hurricane austin said 
the university is setting up a speakers bureau to talk about 
psychological trauma to schools churches and businesses 
the charleston county mental health center has offered a 24hour 
mobile crisis unit since sunday that allows doctors to send a nurse 
and a social worker into the field to prescribe medication for 
stress 
southern pines has set up a crisis line and referral service for 
people having problems the crisis line in operation since monday 
is taking hundreds of calls a day on five lines officials said 
residents should not isolate themselves and should talk about 
their feelings with family or friends 
the main thing is to be aware that these feelings can occur 
people should be open to sharing their experience said dr 
stephen mcleodbryant medical director for the countys mental 
health center 
anxiety can also lead to flashbacks if the wind gusts and 
rattles the windows people might wake up in a cold sweat and feel 
like theyre back in a hurricane mcleodbryant said 
if you hold in these emotions you could develop emotional and 
physical problems its going to come out in some way ms foley 
said 
thousands of people are without homes or still lack basic 
necessities such as electrical service and water others have been 
unable to return to their jobs 
but experts advise residents to try to get back to normal as 
quickly as possible even if its something as simple as going to 
bed and getting up at the same time 
doctors also advise residents not to vent their anger at 
spouses loved ones or public officials energy should be targeted 
to rebuilding 
dealing with these emotions makes you look at whats really 
important in your life it helps you put things in perspective 
ms foley said 
