<TEXT>
school reform the subject of president bushs 
just competed summit with the governors is following a unique 
pattern in americas third largest school system as one chicago 
educator put it the nation has never had a plan like this 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
parents will wield unprecedented power to shape 
public education in chicago following elections this month that 
culminate sweeping reforms in the school system often labeled the 
nations worst 
on oct 1112 voters will elect members to 540 local councils 
which will oversee the citys 603 schools 
the councils each composed of six parents and five other 
members including teachers principals and local residents without 
schoolchildren will have authority to hire and fire principals 
develop school improvement plans and spend money 
its the worst system in the country parents cant do any 
worse than the current system said norman hodgson a father of 
two and candidate for a council that will serve his kindergarten 
daughters northwest side elementary school 
the councils are a key element of a new reform package aimed at 
decentralizing the board of educations powers and eliminating 
deepseated problems that have given chicagos public schools a 
reputation as the nations worst 
and nearly everyone who has a stake in the city from hispanic 
lawmakers and black community activists to white corporate 
executives is participating in a mobilization effort to get 
parents and others involved 
critics say the decentralization goes too far putting too much 
power in the hands of those unequipped to deal with it they say 
schools cant be expected to cure ills that stem from broken 
families 
but reformers argue that by getting parents involved the plan 
will help break a vicious cycle of problems that may begin in 
povertystricken homes but has spilled over into schools and 
created generations of apathetic educators too willing to accept 
the status quo 
one of the changes we hope will happen is teachers and 
principals will stop blaming the families and start thinking about 
what they can do to make a difference said donald moore 
executive director of designs for change an education research and 
advisory council that helped shape the reform package 
who knows more about educating their children than parents 
along with educators weve got to work together hodgson said 
that is the battle cry of the numerous corporations community 
and civic organizations all trying to make sure the reform plan 
passed last year by the state legislature gets off on the right 
foot 
grassroots organizing efforts by groups like designs for change 
have sent volunteers into the citys housing projects going 
doortodoor to recruit candidates for the twoyear council 
positions school officials sought 10000 candidates but passed 
the mark by thursday with nearly 14650 although some 
neighborhoods still lack full slates 
corporations have donated hundreds of thousands of dollars and 
clergymen have devoted sermons to urging their congregations to get 
involved and vote for the sake of the schools 410000 children 
everyones talking about it said lucy moore a 58yearold 
grandmother running in an poor black neighborhood on the south side 
so far everyone that i talk to in the neighborhood says they 
are interested she said they say they will vote they say our 
children are at stake they are our future 
each council will include six parents two teachers and two 
community residents without schoolchildren school staffs will 
elect the teacher members the 11th member of each council will be 
the principal of the school the council oversees in some cases 
councils will oversee more than one school 
council powers will include signing principals to fouryear 
performance contracts and deciding whether to renew what 
essentially were lifetime jobs before reform 
principals will have authority to hire teachers and dismiss them 
after 45 days probation regardless of seniority before teachers 
deemed unsatisfactory had a year to improve politics and seniority 
often made principals hire teachers they didnt want 
before the central board had to approve every little thing 
that the school did now their role is much more to be a monitor to 
enforce minimum standards said donald moore of designs for 
change 
the chicago teachers union which represents 28000 district 
employees including nearly 21800 teachers did not return 
telephone calls seeking comment 
reform also means shifting more money to schools that serve the 
most lowincome students and eliminating supefluous administrative 
jobs 500 already have been cut for example the school system 
trimmed some positions when it stopped testing teacher applicants 
to prove their state certification 
chicagos school budget this year is 226 billion up about 
200 million over last year while reform does not call for more 
state money it involves shifting budget money to give a larger 
share to educating low income students moore said 
and 40 million that resulted from eliminating board jobs is 
being pumped into the reform effort he added 
what this law does it to put a mechanism in place so that 
principals and teachers will be held accountable for their schools 
by the people who have the most at stake that is primarily by 
parents moore said 
chicagos woes gained nationwide scrutiny in 1987 when william 
bennett then president reagans education secretary labeled the 
citys schools the worst in the nation the reform effort has put 
the system in the national spotlight again 
chicagos school reform is the most fundamental reorganization 
of a big city school system since the early part of the 20th 
century said david cohen professor of education and social 
policy at michigan state university 
i think a lot of people thought the chicago system was about 
as poor as any system in the country said norm fruchter senior 
consultant for the academy of educational development a new 
yorkbased group that analyzes urban school systems 
