energy futures prices rose in moderate trading 
thursday reflecting general optimism that opecs latest accord 
would not mean higher oil production or weaker prices 
the organization of petroleum exporting countries concluded a 
fiveday meeting on wednesday by increasing its stated production 
ceiling to 205 million barrels a day from 195 million 
analysts said the higher quota more accurately reflects the 
demand for opec oil and should help maintain relatively stable 
prices through the fourth quarter without raising actual production 
although there is disappointment in the outcome people 
realize that demand is still running at a high level said tom 
bentz director of futures trading at united energy inc 
